In the realm of [public transport](/Public_transport), a peculiar phenomenon occurs, a service that doesn't quite commit to the full journey. It's known as a short turn, a short working, or a turn-back. Imagine a [bus route](/Bus_route) or a rail line that, for reasons ranging from the mundane to the inconvenient, decides to call it a day before reaching its advertised end. These aren't the rogue vehicles acting out; they're often meticulously scheduled, appearing in [timetables](/Public_transport_timetable) like planned detours from the main narrative. Public transport authorities, ever the pragmatists, deploy these short turns for a smorgasbord of reasons: perhaps the tracks are a mess, the buses are playing a game of [bus bunching](/Bus_bunching), or simply because the demand for the latter half of the route is as sparse as a polite conversation with a politician.

These services, while economical, often necessitate a bit of spatial gymnastics. Buses, bless their rubber tires, can usually manage a quick U-turn on a street corner. Trams, however, are a different beast. Their short turns can be dictated by the presence of a [balloon loop](/Balloon_loop), a dedicated track that allows them to gracefully reverse direction. This, of course, limits where these mid-route conclusions can take place. Rail services, whether [rapid transit](/Rapid_transit) or [commuter rail](/Commuter_rail), have their own set of requirements: [crossovers](/Railroad_switch), loops, or other specialized trackwork are essential for these vehicles to perform their truncated duties.

### Purposes

#### Demand for services

Short turns are a strategic tool, particularly on routes where the demand for service dwindles in the latter sections. It's a way to trim the fat, reduce operating costs by not running empty carriages or buses to destinations with minimal ridership. [1]:118 This economic advantage, however, doesn't always mean fewer vehicles are needed overall to maintain the full service schedule. [1]:457 Sometimes, a more complex solution, like branching routes, is employed to offer frequent service on the main trunk while the offshoots receive less attention.

#### Crowd management

Beyond the economic calculus, short turns can also be a tactical maneuver for crowd control. By strategically scheduling a mix of full-length and short-turn trips, operators can attempt to mitigate [overcrowding](/Overcrowding). The uneven intervals between services, especially those originating from a short-turn layover point, can sometimes help in accommodating a larger influx of passengers. [4]:3-75, 7-6

#### Unscheduled short turns

Then there are the unscheduled short turns, the unplanned interruptions to the predictable rhythm of public transport. These usually arise from disruptions, delays, or the aforementioned [bus bunching](/Bus_bunching). When vehicles cluster together, some might be diverted to provide extra service in the opposite direction. It’s a way for a vehicle to claw back lost time and, coincidentally, benefit passengers waiting for a ride in the other direction. While a useful tool for transit managers navigating chaos, it’s hardly a smooth experience for the passengers on board the abruptly terminating vehicle. [3]:478

The inconvenience for those passengers is undeniable. They are unceremoniously deposited before their intended destination, a disruption that often draws criticism from the public and the media. In [Toronto](/Toronto), for instance, a review of the [Toronto Transit Commission](/Toronto_Transit_Commission) revealed over 333,000 short-turned trips between January 2012 and September 2014. [6] It seems even in the meticulously planned world of transit, spontaneity can be a significant irritant.

### History

The concept of a "short turn" isn't exactly a modern invention. An early English-language glimpse into this practice can be found in *A New English Dictionary On Historical Principles*. In its definition of "short running," it cites an 1855 document describing [stagecoach](/Stagecoach) services in [Cornwall](/Cornwall). The passage suggests that the popularity of these coaches was so immense that "short-running coaches were few," implying that the longer routes were the norm due to high patronage. It’s a quaint reminder that the desire for efficiency and tailored service has a long lineage.

### Short turns by mode of transport

#### Buses

##### Trolleybuses

[Trolleybuses](/Trolleybus), those electric workhorses drawing power from overhead lines, present a unique challenge for short turns. Their dependence on those wires means short turns are only feasible where the infrastructure exists. However, advancements in battery technology have introduced a new flexibility. Some modern trolleybuses can operate for limited distances off-wire, powered by batteries or auxiliary engines. This allows for short turns at more varied locations. [8] The progress has been significant; what was once a mere 3.2 km (2 mi) off-wire capability in 1983 [8] has evolved to trolleybuses routinely covering over 16 mi (25 km) by 2023. [9] This "off-wire" capability is becoming a crucial feature for adapting to changing service demands.

##### Battery-electric buses

[Battery-electric buses](/Battery-electric_bus) offer even greater freedom for short-turn operations, as they are largely unburdened by fixed infrastructure. Their primary limitation is the need for periodic recharging. Many operators strategically place chargers at terminals, which might not always align with the planned short-turn points. This can lead to the inefficient practice of [deadheading](/Dead_mileage) – running empty buses back to charging stations, potentially negating the cost savings of short turns. A 2024 study by scholars from Xi'an University of Posts and Telecommunications and [Beijing Jiaotong University](/Beijing_Jiaotong_University) highlighted this very issue, suggesting that the costs associated with deadheading could indeed outweigh the benefits of short-turn services in certain scenarios. [10]

##### Bus rapid transit

[Bus rapid transit](/Bus_rapid_transit) (BRT) systems, by their nature, operate on dedicated infrastructure, separate from the general traffic. This necessitates the provision of specific turnaround points for short-turn services. In some BRT systems, like the [Metrobüs](/Metrobus_(Istanbul)) in [Istanbul](/Istanbul), short turns are not the exception but the rule, forming the majority of services. While full-length services do exist, the short-turn routes are integral to the Metrobüs system's operation, which is renowned for its high frequency, with buses arriving as often as every 15 seconds.

#### Streetcars and trams

Streetcars, or trams, require dedicated track infrastructure for their short-turn maneuvers. In systems with single-ended cars, like the [Toronto streetcar system](/Toronto_streetcar_system), short turns necessitate either loops integrated into city streets or dedicated off-street [balloon loops](/Balloon_loop). Toronto is a prime example where both scheduled and unscheduled short turns are a common occurrence.

In [Melbourne](/Melbourne), the tram system, the world's largest, officially refers to these truncated services as "short workings." However, they've also earned the somewhat whimsical nickname "ghost trams" due to the confusion they can sometimes generate. From 1970 to 2012, these short workings were often identified by numbers unrelated to their parent routes, leading to a rather opaque system. For instance, route 31 was a short working of [route 48](/Melbourne_tram_route_48), and short workings of [route 1](/Melbourne_tram_route_1) were identified by various numbers like 2, 2A, 4, and 21. [11] The privatization of the system in 1999 further complicated matters, with many short workings disappearing from public timetables. A route reorganization in 2012 introduced a clearer nomenclature: the suffix "d" indicates trams terminating at their depot, while "a" signifies other short workings. [12][13][14]

#### Rapid transit (subway, metro)

Short-turn services are a vital component of many [rapid transit](/Rapid_transit) (subway or metro) systems. The [New York City Subway](/New_York_City_Subway) is a prime example, employing short turns across its vast network. Some are driven by passenger demand, like the weekend [5 trains](/5_(New_York_City_Subway_service)) that start at [Eastchester](/Eastchester%E2%80%93Dyre_Avenue_station) but terminate at [Bowling Green](/Bowling_Green_station), then utilize the disused inner track of the [Old South Ferry loop](/South_Ferry/Whitehall_Street_station) to turn around. [15] During peak hours, when terminal stations struggle to accommodate the full rush-hour service, short turns become essential. This is evident with some [F trains](/F_(New_York_City_Subway_service)), which short turn at [Kings Highway](/Kings_Highway_station_(IND_Culver_Line)) instead of completing their full journey to [Coney Island](/Coney_Island%E2%80%93Stillwell_Avenue_station). [16]

#### Commuter rail

Short-turn services are also a feature of [commuter rail](/Commuter_rail) and [regional rail](/Regional_rail) networks. The [Réseau Express Régional](/R%C3%A9seau_Express_R%C3%A9gional) (RER) in the [Paris Region](/%C3%8Ele-de-France) of [France](/France) offers a particularly intricate example. Its system, with a high-capacity tunnel through central Paris and multiple suburban branches, relies heavily on short turns to manage passenger flow and alleviate congestion in the city center. These services are communicated through a complex system of six-character "mission codes," which denote the train's destination and stopping pattern. During disruptions, maintenance, or special events, these codes are updated to reflect the altered service. [17]

For instance, an RER A train displaying the mission code "DROP" indicates a destination of [Noisy-le-Grand – Mont d'Est](/Noisy-le-Grand_%E2%80%93_Mont_d%27Est_station), one of the designated short-turn termini on the A4 branch. Similarly, planned maintenance on the A1 branch to [Saint-Germain-en-Laye](/Saint-Germain-en-Laye_station) might necessitate trains short-turning at [Le Vésinet–Le Pecq](/V%C3%A9sinet%E2%80%93Le_Pecq_station), a situation identified by the mission code "XOUD." [17]

#### Monorail

The [Wuppertal Schwebebahn](/Wuppertal_Schwebebahn), a suspended monorail in [Wuppertal](/Wuppertal), [Germany](/Germany), once had the capability for short-turn services. The Kluse station featured a turning loop, sadly destroyed during World War II. Later, the Zoo/Stadion station incorporated a loop and a turntable, the latter operating from 1974 until 2002 when environmental concerns led to its closure. Since then, all services traverse the entire 13.3 km (8.3 mi) line. [18][19]

Monorail systems, in general, require substantial and intricate switches for short turns. The [Chongqing Rail Transit](/Chongqing_Rail_Transit) [Line 3](/Line_3_(Chongqing_Rail_Transit)), reputedly the world's busiest monorail, is an exception, equipped for short turns at numerous points. This is unusual for monorails due to the significant size, complexity, and cost of the necessary [switches](/Monorail). Line 3, stretching 53.1 km (30 mi) with 39 stations, has eight equipped for turning trains around, facilitating multiple short-turn service patterns. [20]

A 2021 study by scholars from [Southwest Jiaotong University](/Southwest_Jiaotong_University) and [Hong Kong Polytechnic University](/Hong_Kong_Polytechnic_University) explored the operations of Line 3, proposing a mathematical model to optimize short-turn services. Their research suggested that optimized routes could lead to a 4% reduction in operating costs while maintaining or improving passenger experience. [20]

### In popular culture

The phenomenon of unscheduled short turns on the [Toronto streetcar system](/Toronto_streetcar_system) has even inspired a streetcar-themed restaurant in [Toronto](/Toronto) called "Short Turn." Located on [Queen Street](/Queen_Street,_Toronto), it features salvaged fixtures from retired streetcars and signage reminiscent of destination displays. [21][22] It’s a curious testament to how even the inconveniences of public transport can find their way into the cultural landscape.